06850nam a22013215i 9781400832569DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759575  a9781400832569  a(DE-B1597)576303  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBM195 7aHIS0140002bisacsh1 aMyers, David N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResisting History :bHistoricism and Its Discontents in German-Jewish Thought /cDavid N. Myers. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (269 p.) :b5 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews, Christians, and Muslims from the Ancient to the Modern World ;v3600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA NOTE ON THE COVER -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER ONE Jewish Historicism and Its Discontents: An Introduction -- tCHAPTER TWO Hermann Cohen and the Problem of History at the Fin de Siècle -- tCHAPTER THREE Franz Rosenzweig and the Rise of Theological Anti-Historicism -- tCHAPTER FOUR Anti-Historicism and the Theological-Political Predicament in Weimar Germany: The Case of Leo Strauss -- tCHAPTER FIVE Isaac Breuer and the Jewish Path to Metageschichte -- tCHAPTER SIX From Conclusion to Opening: A Word on Influence, German Jews, and the Cultural History of Ideas -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNineteenth-century European thought, especially in Germany, was increasingly dominated by a new historicist impulse to situate every event, person, or text in its particular context. At odds with the transcendent claims of philosophy and--more significantly--theology, historicism came to be attacked by its critics for reducing human experience to a series of disconnected moments, each of which was the product of decidedly mundane, rather than sacred, origins. By the late nineteenth century and into the Weimar period, historicism was seen by many as a grinding force that corroded social values and was emblematic of modern society's gravest ills. Resisting History examines the backlash against historicism, focusing on four major Jewish thinkers. David Myers situates these thinkers in proximity to leading Protestant thinkers of the time, but argues that German Jews and Christians shared a complex cultural and discursive world best understood in terms of exchange and adaptation rather than influence.After examining the growing dominance of the new historicist thinking in the nineteenth century, the book analyzes the critical responses of Hermann Cohen, Franz Rosenzweig, Leo Strauss, and Isaac Breuer. For this fascinating and diverse quartet of thinkers, historicism posed a stark challenge to the ongoing vitality of Judaism in the modern world. And yet, as they set out to dilute or eliminate its destructive tendencies, these thinkers often made recourse to the very tools and methods of historicism. In doing so, they demonstrated the utter inescapability of historicism in modern culture, whether approached from a Christian or Jewish perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHistoricismxHistory. 0aJewish learning and scholarshipzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewish learning and scholarshipzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJudaismxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aAgudat Yisrael.  aBalfour Declaration.  aBenjamin, Walter.  aBreuer, Salomon.  aCassirer, Ernst.  aConservative Revolution.  aDavos conference.  aDenominationalism.  aDilthey, Wilhelm.  aEhrenfreund, Jacques.  aEnlightenment.  aErets Yisrael.  aFischer, Kuno.  aFrankfurt am Main.  aFunkenstein, Amos.  aGeiger, Abraham.  aGeisteswissenschaft.